Sentences spoken with different emotions

The dataset consists of 1176 short sentences, each spoken with emotion by a young adult female (ref). There is an equal number of sentences for each of 7 emotions: anger, disgust, fear, happy, neutral, pleasant surprise, and sad. The words in sentences are also identical across emotions. Each sentence has seven acoustic characteristics: sentence duration, F0 mean, F0 SD, F0 slope, spectral center-of-gravity, intensity mean, and intensity SD.

How do characteristics correlate?

Linear discriminant analysis: Which acoustic characteristics best distinguish emotions?

The dataset of 1176 sentences is split into a training set (n=882) and a test set (n=294); both sets have equal numbers of each emotion.

Using the two predictors with the largest F values, the biggest loss of accuracy comes from a mix-up between Disgust and Sad sentences.

Table 2. t tests: Differences between Disgust and Sad
Predictor t values
Sentence duration 19.189
F0 mean -1.5012
F0 SD 8.047
F0 slope 4.718
Spectral CoG 26.101
Intensity mean -23.455
Intensity SD 8.1817

Adding a third acoustic predictor that best distinguishes Disgust and Sad sentences (Spectral CoG), model accuracy increases by almost 10 percentage points for the test set, and is within 3 points of a model with all predictors. Adding predictors beyond 3 does not lead to any significant improvement in model performance (95% confidence intervals shown in blue).
